xxl.collections
Class EmptyContainer

java.lang.Object
  |
  +--xxl.collections.Container
        |
        +--xxl.collections.EmptyContainer
public class EmptyContainer
extends Container

This class provides an empty container. In other words, this container is not able to contain an element. Therefore, every method that inserts elements into the container always throw an UnsupportedOperationException. The methods that accesses elements of the container always throw a NoSuchElementException. This class is useful when you have to return a container of some kind, but don³t have any elements the container points to.

Example usage (1). 

     // create a new empty container

     EmptyContainer container = EmptyContainer.DEFAULT_INSTANCE;

     // println the number of elements contained by the container

     System.out.println(container.size());

     // create an iteration over 20 random Integers (between 0 and 100)

     Cursor cursor = new RandomIntegers(100, 20);

     // catch UnsupportedOperationExceptions

     try {

         // insert all elements of the given iterator

         while (cursor.hasNext())
             container.insert(cursor.next());
     }
     catch (UnsupportedOperationException uoe) {
         System.out.println(uoe.getMessage());
     }

     // println the number of elements contained by the container

     System.out.println(container.size());

     // close the open bag and cursor after use

     container.close();
     cursor.close();

See Also:
Converter, ConvertableConverter, Cursor, EmptyCursor, Function, Iterator, NoSuchElementException

DEFAULT_INSTANCE

public static final EmptyContainer DEFAULT_INSTANCE
This instance can be used for getting a default instance of EmptyContainer. It is similar to the Singleton Design Pattern (for further details see Creational Patterns, Prototype in Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software by Erich Gamma, Richard Helm, Ralph Johnson, and John Vlissides) except that there are no mechanisms to avoid the creation of other instances of EmptyContainer.

insert

public Object insert(Object object,
                     boolean unfix)
              throws UnsupportedOperationException
Inserts a new object into the container and returns the unique identifier that the container has been associated to the object. The identifier can be reused again when the object is deleted from the container. If unfixed, the object can be removed from the buffer. Otherwise, it has to be kept in the buffer until an unfix() is called.
This implementation always throws an UnsupportedOperationException.
Overrides:
insert in class Container
Parameters:
object - is the new object.
unfix - signals whether the object can be removed from the underlying buffer.
Returns:
the identifier of the object.

unfix

public void unfix(Object id)
           throws NoSuchElementException
Unfixes the Object with identifier id. This method throws an exception when no element with an identifier id is in the container. After one call of unfix the buffer is allowed to remove the object (although the objects have been fixed more than once).
This implementation always throws a NoSuchElementException because the container is empty.
